The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Business Briefs

 New Delhi, April 6: The Confederation of Indian Industry (CII) today warned that any further tightening of money supply by the Reserve Bank will trigger a slowdown of the economy. There are already emerging signals in the form of slowdown in the automotive sector and retail banking, CII president R. Seshasayee said. He said while inflation control is at the top of the national agenda, it is important that growth is not traded off in the bargain.

 Mumbai, April 6: Indias forex reserves increased $1.433 billion to $199.179 billion in the week ended March 30 against $197.746 billion in the previous week. The reserves had increased by $1.789 billion in the week ended March 23. The foreign currency assets rose by $1.532 billion to $191.924 billion.

 Paris, April 6: Arcelor Mittal has raised its offer for minority shares in Arcelor Brazil to 51.27 reals per share from 32.79 reals after Brazilian market regulator CVM demanded an increase. The new offer will involve a maximum cash payout of 10.9 billion reals.

 New Delhi, April 6: Chhattisgarh has emerged as Indias top destination for entrepreneurs with investment proposals of Rs 107,899 crore, followed by Karnataka and Orissa, while Gujarat has been pushed to the fourth position.

 Calcutta, April 6: BEML chairman and managing director V. Natarajan said the company was in the process of filing a red herring prospectus (RHP) with Sebi this month. The company plans to hit the market in the first half of June.




